.
 Applying the same type of analysis as above to the 2PIEA 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetric theory one finds that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is invariant and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{ab}$
\end_inset

 transform as a vector and symmetric rank two tensor respectively.
 As before 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is invariant off-shell.
 The shift of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 gives the 2PI version of the master Ward identity
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta\Gamma}{\delta\varphi_{a}}i\epsilon_{A}T_{ab}^{A}\varphi_{b}+\frac{\delta\Gamma}{\delta\Delta_{ab}}i\epsilon_{A}\left(T_{ac}^{A}\Delta_{cb}+T_{bc}^{A}\Delta_{ac}\right)=0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The second term accounts for the additional transformation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 in the 2PIEA formalism.
 Taking derivatives with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

, stripping factors of 
\begin_inset Formula $i\epsilon_{A}$
\end_inset

 and applying the 2PI equations of motion (recall 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2pi-eom-varphi"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2pi-eom-Delta"

\end_inset

 reproduced here for convenience:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\delta\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]}{\delta\varphi} & = & -J-K\varphi,\\
\frac{\delta\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]}{\delta\Delta} & = & -\frac{1}{2}i\hbar K,
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

), gives a set of 2PI WIs which are now complicated by the fact that there
 are multiple types of correlation function of the same rank appearing.
 For example, there are now two different two point functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta^{2}\Gamma}{\delta\varphi_{a}\delta\varphi_{b}},\ \frac{\delta\Gamma}{\delta\Delta_{ab}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and three different four point functions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta^{4}\Gamma}{\delta\varphi_{a}\delta\varphi_{b}\delta\varphi_{c}\delta\varphi_{d}},\ \frac{\delta^{3}\Gamma}{\delta\varphi_{a}\delta\varphi_{b}\delta\Delta_{cd}},\ \frac{\delta^{2}\Gamma}{\delta\Delta_{ab}\delta\Delta_{cd}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which are, in general truncations, all different.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To illustrate the various 1PI and 2PI functions recall the equivalence relations
hip between the 1PIEA and 2PIEA 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma\left[\varphi\right]=\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\left[\varphi\right]\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\left[\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

 is the solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]/\delta\Delta=0$
\end_inset

 at fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 Using that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta^{2}\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\left[\varphi\right]\right]}{\delta\varphi_{a}\delta\varphi_{b}}=\Delta_{ab}^{-1}\left[\varphi\right]=\Delta_{0ab}^{-1}\left[\varphi\right]-\Sigma_{ab}\left[\varphi,\Delta\left[\varphi\right]\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Sigma_{ab}\left[\varphi,\Delta\left[\varphi\right]\right]=\frac{2i}{\hbar}\left(\frac{\delta\Gamma_{2}\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]}{\delta\Delta_{ab}}\right)_{\Delta=\Delta\left[\varphi\right]},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

one can relate derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left[\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 to mixed derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 For example,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{abc}=\frac{\delta^{2}\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\left[\varphi\right]\right]}{\delta\varphi_{a}\delta\varphi_{b}\delta\varphi_{c}}=V_{0abc}\left[\varphi\right]-\frac{\delta\Sigma_{ab}\left[\varphi,\Delta\left[\varphi\right]\right]}{\delta\varphi_{c}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Being careful to use the chain rule, one obtains
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
V_{abc} & =V_{0abc}\left[\varphi\right]-\left(\frac{\delta\Sigma_{ab}\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]}{\delta\varphi_{c}}\right)_{\Delta=\Delta\left[\varphi\right]}-\left(\frac{\delta\Delta_{de}}{\delta\varphi_{c}}\frac{\delta\Sigma_{ab}\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]}{\delta\Delta_{de}}\right)_{\Delta=\Delta\left[\varphi\right]}\nonumber \\
 & =V_{0abc}\left[\varphi\right]-\left(\frac{\delta\Sigma_{ab}}{\delta\varphi_{c}}\right)_{\Delta=\Delta\left[\varphi\right]}+V_{cde}\Delta_{df}\left[\varphi\right]\Delta_{eg}\left[\varphi\right]\left(\frac{\delta\Sigma_{ab}}{\delta\Delta_{fg}}\right)_{\Delta=\Delta\left[\varphi\right]},
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the second line is reached using 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\Delta=-\Delta\left(\delta\Delta^{-1}\right)\Delta$
\end_inset

 as an intermediate step.
 Continuing in this way one can find a set of identities relating derivatives
 of the 1PIEA and the 2PIEA evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\Delta\left[\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to also find identities which do not require 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\Delta\left[\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

 by taking derivatives of the 2PI equations of motion and using relations
 involving 
\begin_inset Formula $W\left[J,K\right]$
\end_inset

, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta J_{a}/\delta\varphi_{b}=\left(\delta\varphi_{b}/\delta J_{a}\right)^{-1}=\left(\delta^{2}W\left[J,K\right]/\delta J_{b}\delta J_{a}\right)^{-1}=-\Delta_{ba}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and so on.
 This allows one to find that, for example,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{ba}^{-1}=\frac{\delta^{2}\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]}{\delta\varphi_{b}\delta\varphi_{a}}+\frac{2i}{\hbar}\frac{\delta^{2}\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]}{\delta\varphi_{b}\delta\Delta_{ad}}\varphi_{d}+\frac{2i}{\hbar}\frac{\delta\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]}{\delta\Delta_{ab}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

regardless of the values of the external sources.
 If the derivatives are taken holding 
\begin_inset Formula $K=0$
\end_inset

 fixed (so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\Delta\left[\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

) the second and third term vanish, reproducing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{ba}^{-1}=\delta^{2}\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\left[\varphi\right]\right]/\delta\varphi_{b}\delta\varphi_{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta/\delta\varphi_{c}$
\end_inset

 of the master 2PI WI and using the previous result in the absence of external
 sources one finds
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=\Delta_{ca}^{-1}T_{ab}^{A}\varphi_{b}+\frac{\delta^{2}\Gamma}{\delta\varphi_{c}\delta\Delta_{ab}}\left(T_{ad}^{A}\Delta_{db}+T_{bd}^{A}\Delta_{ad}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is the 2PI analogue of Goldstone's theorem.
 Note that there is no reason for the second term to vanish in generic truncatio
ns of the 2PIEA, though it must vanish in the exact theory since there 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 is equal to the 1PI value for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{ca}^{-1}T_{ab}\varphi_{b}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In an approximation however, this no longer holds and the 2PI function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 no longer faithfully represents the propagator of the Goldstone bosons,
 which now have an unphysical mass.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see this explicitly, consider substituting in the explicit saddle point
 formula for the 2PIEA 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2piea"

\end_inset

 in the Hartree-Fock approximation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]=S\left[\varphi\right]+\frac{i\hbar}{2}\mathrm{Tr}\ln\Delta^{-1}+\frac{i\hbar}{2}\mathrm{Tr}\left(\Delta_{0}^{-1}\Delta-1\right)+\frac{\hbar^{2}\lambda}{24}\left(\Delta_{aa}\Delta_{bb}+2\Delta_{ab}\Delta_{ab}\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta^{2}\Gamma}{\delta\varphi_{c}\left(z\right)\delta\Delta_{ab}\left(x,y\right)}=-\frac{i\hbar\lambda}{6}\left(\delta_{ab}\varphi_{c}+\delta_{ca}\varphi_{b}+\delta_{bc}\varphi_{a}\right)\delta^{\left(4\right)}\left(x-y\right)\delta^{\left(4\right)}\left(x-z\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

whence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
0 & = & \int_{x}\Delta_{ca}^{-1}\left(z,x\right)T_{ab}^{A}\varphi_{b}\left(x\right)\nonumber \\
 &  & -\frac{i\hbar\lambda}{6}\left(\delta_{ab}\varphi_{c}\left(z\right)+\delta_{ca}\varphi_{b}\left(z\right)+\delta_{bc}\varphi_{a}\left(z\right)\right)\left(T_{ad}^{A}\Delta_{db}\left(z,z\right)+T_{bd}^{A}\Delta_{ad}\left(z,z\right)\right)\nonumber \\
 &  & +\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right),
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where all spacetime arguments are now made explicit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=v\left(-m_{G}^{2}\right)-\frac{i\hbar\lambda}{3}v\left(\Delta_{H}\left(z,z\right)-\Delta_{G}\left(z,z\right)\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left(g,N\right)$
\end_inset

 and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=v\Delta_{Ng}\left(z,z\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left(g,g'\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The second equation is satisfied if the mixed Higgs-Goldstone propagators
 vanish, but the first equation implies a violation of Goldstone's theorem.
 Indeed, in the broken symmetry regime
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m_{G}^{2}=-\frac{i\hbar\lambda}{3}v\left(\Delta_{H}\left(z,z\right)-\Delta_{G}\left(z,z\right)\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The propagators evaluated at coincident points are quadratically divergent
 in four dimensions, so the difference
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i\Delta_{H}\left(z,z\right)-i\Delta_{G}\left(z,z\right)=i\int_{p}\frac{m_{H}^{2}-m_{G}^{2}}{\left(p^{2}-m_{H}^{2}\right)\left(p^{2}-m_{G}^{2}\right)}+\mathcal{T}_{H}^{\mathrm{th}}-\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{th}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is logarithmically divergent and requires renormalisation.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{H/G}^{\mathrm{th}}$
\end_inset

 are the finite thermal Bose-Einstein contributions
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{T}_{H/G}^{\mathrm{th}}=\int_{\boldsymbol{k}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{\boldsymbol{k}^{2}+m_{H/G}^{2}}}\frac{1}{\mathrm{e}^{\beta\sqrt{\boldsymbol{k}^{2}+m_{H/G}^{2}}}-1}.
\]

\end_inset

 In general, the renormalised form of the difference can be written
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i\Delta_{H}\left(z,z\right)-i\Delta_{G}\left(z,z\right)=\left(m_{H}^{2}-m_{G}^{2}\right)\left[C+F\left(m_{H}^{2},m_{G}^{2}\right)\right]+\mathcal{T}_{H}^{\mathrm{th}}-\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{th}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a real scheme dependent constant and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(m_{H}^{2},m_{G}^{2}\right)=\int_{0}^{m_{G}^{2}}\mathrm{d}\mu^{2}\int_{p}\frac{i}{\left(p^{2}-m_{H}^{2}\right)\left(p^{2}-\mu^{2}\right)^{2}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is finite and equal to zero if 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 (explicitly 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(m_{H}^{2},xm_{H}^{2}\right)=\frac{1}{16\pi^{2}}\frac{x\ln x}{x-1}$
\end_inset

).
 In the modified minimal subtraction scheme (
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathrm{MS}}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C=\frac{1}{16\pi^{2}}\ln\left(\frac{m_{H}^{2}}{\mu^{2}}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m_{G}^{2}=-\frac{\hbar\lambda}{3}v\left[\left(m_{H}^{2}-m_{G}^{2}\right)\left(C+F\left(m_{H}^{2},m_{G}^{2}\right)\right)+\mathcal{T}_{H}^{\mathrm{th}}-\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{th}}\right]+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which only admits 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 as a solution at zero temperature if 
\begin_inset Formula $C=0$
\end_inset

.
 This can be achieved in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mathrm{MS}}$
\end_inset

 by choosing the renormalisation point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=m_{H}$
\end_inset

 (a similar choice can be made in any other subtraction scheme).
 However, once this is done all renormalisation constants are fixed and
 one has 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G}^{2}\neq0$
\end_inset

 at any other temperature in the symmetry breaking regime.
 As a result Goldstone's theorem is violated at finite temperature and the
 unphysical mass of the Goldstone bosons is responsible for also changing
 the symmetry breaking phase transition from second order to first order.
 The only other 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 solution also has 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{H}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 which is only possible at the critical temperature of the phase transition.
 To find the critical temperature it is necessary to actually solve the
 2PI gap equation.
\end_layout

