\begin_layout Standard
In order to exhibit the properties of solutions of the 2PI equations of
 motion in more detail it is necessary to discuss the renormalisation process.
 Renormalisation is a necessary process to extract any physical observables
 from a QFT.
 In a renormalisable theory all divergences can be absorbed in a redefinition
 of a fixed finite number of coupling constants, yielding a predictive theory
 once the couplings are fixed experimentally.
 In a non-renormalisable theory the divergences cannot be removed by a finite
 number of coupling constants, but the required infinitude of constants
 can be organised order by order in powers of an energy scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 so that only a finite number are required to give a predictive 
\emph on
effective field theory
\emph default
 accurate to some fixed order in 
\begin_inset Formula $E/\Lambda$
\end_inset

 for low energy processes 
\begin_inset Formula $E\ll\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 However, the number of couplings required grows as 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and the theory loses predictivity altogether at the cutoff scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 The scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 theory considered above and in the rest of this thesis is renormalisable
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $d\leq4$
\end_inset

 spacetime dimensions.
 Elegant general discussions of renormalisation theory can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zinn-Justin1990,zinn-justin_phase_2007"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To renormalise the 2PIEA one first replaces all bare parameters by their
 renormalised counterparts, which are represented here by the same letters
 for simplicity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left(\phi,\varphi,v\right) & \to & Z^{1/2}\left(\phi,\varphi,v\right),\\
m^{2} & \to & Z^{-1}Z_{\Delta}^{-1}\left(m^{2}+\delta m^{2}\right),\\
\lambda & \to & Z^{-2}\left(\lambda+\delta\lambda\right),\\
\Delta & \to & ZZ_{\Delta}\Delta,
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{\Delta}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta m^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\lambda$
\end_inset

 are to chosen to cancel divergences.
 Whenever necessary to refer to bare parameters in the remainder of this
 chapter, the subscript 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

B
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 will be used, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{B}^{2}$
\end_inset

 etc.
 Due to the presence of composite operators in the effective action, additional
 counterterms are required compared to the standard perturbation theory:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta m_{0}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\lambda_{0}$
\end_inset

 for terms in the bare action, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta m_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 for one-loop terms, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\lambda_{1}^{A}$
\end_inset

 for terms of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{a}\phi_{a}\Delta_{bb}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\lambda_{1}^{B}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{a}\phi_{b}\Delta_{ab}$
\end_inset

 terms, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\lambda_{2}^{A}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{aa}\Delta_{bb}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\lambda_{2}^{B}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{ab}\Delta_{ab}$
\end_inset

.
 Altogether there are nine renormalisation constants which must be eliminated
 by imposing nine conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resulting renormalised 2PIEA in the Hartree-Fock approximation is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\right] & = & \frac{1}{2}Z\varphi_{a}\left(-\square\right)\varphi_{a}-\frac{1}{2}Z_{\Delta}^{-1}\varphi_{a}\left(m^{2}+\delta m_{0}^{2}\right)\varphi_{a}-\frac{\lambda+\delta\lambda_{0}}{4!}\left(\varphi_{a}\varphi_{a}\right)^{2}+\frac{i\hbar}{2}\mathrm{Tr}\ln\left(Z^{-1}Z_{\Delta}^{-1}\Delta^{-1}\right)\nonumber \\
 &  & -\frac{i\hbar}{2}\left[\left(ZZ_{\Delta}\square+m^{2}+\delta m_{1}^{2}\right)\Delta_{aa}+Z_{\Delta}\frac{\lambda+\delta\lambda_{1}^{A}}{6}\varphi_{a}\varphi_{a}\Delta_{bb}+Z_{\Delta}\frac{\lambda+\delta\lambda_{1}^{B}}{3}\varphi_{a}\varphi_{b}\Delta_{ab}\right]\nonumber \\
 &  & +Z_{\Delta}^{2}\frac{\hbar^{2}\left(\lambda+\delta\lambda_{2}^{A}\right)}{24}\Delta_{aa}\Delta_{bb}+Z_{\Delta}^{2}\frac{\hbar^{2}\left(\lambda+\delta\lambda_{2}^{B}\right)}{12}\Delta_{ab}\Delta_{ab}+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right),
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

which, on using the SSB ansatz 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SSB-ansatz-Delta"

\end_inset

, becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Gamma\left[v,\Delta_{G},\Delta_{H}\right] & =\int_{x}\left(-\frac{1}{2}Z_{\Delta}^{-1}\left(m^{2}+\delta m_{0}^{2}\right)v^{2}-\frac{\lambda+\delta\lambda_{0}}{4!}v^{4}\right)\nonumber \\
 & +\left(N-1\right)\frac{i\hbar}{2}\mathrm{Tr}\ln\left(Z^{-1}Z_{\Delta}^{-1}\Delta_{G}^{-1}\right)+\frac{i\hbar}{2}\mathrm{Tr}\ln\left(Z^{-1}Z_{\Delta}^{-1}\Delta_{H}^{-1}\right)\nonumber \\
 & -\left(N-1\right)\frac{i\hbar}{2}\mathrm{Tr}\left[\left(ZZ_{\Delta}\square+m^{2}+\delta m_{1}^{2}+Z_{\Delta}\frac{\lambda+\delta\lambda_{1}^{A}}{6}v^{2}\right)\Delta_{G}\right]\nonumber \\
 & -\frac{i\hbar}{2}\mathrm{Tr}\left[\left(ZZ_{\Delta}\square+m^{2}+\delta m_{1}^{2}+Z_{\Delta}\frac{3\lambda+\delta\lambda_{1}^{A}+2\delta\lambda_{1}^{B}}{6}v^{2}\right)\Delta_{H}\right]\nonumber \\
 & +Z_{\Delta}^{2}\frac{\hbar^{2}}{24}\left[\left(N+1\right)\lambda+\left(N-1\right)\delta\lambda_{2}^{A}+2\delta\lambda_{2}^{B}\right]\left(N-1\right)\Delta_{G}\Delta_{G}\nonumber \\
 & +Z_{\Delta}^{2}\frac{\hbar^{2}\left(\lambda+\delta\lambda_{2}^{A}\right)}{12}\left(N-1\right)\Delta_{G}\Delta_{H}+Z_{\Delta}^{2}\frac{\hbar^{2}}{24}\left[3\lambda+\delta\lambda_{2}^{A}+2\delta\lambda_{2}^{B}\right]\Delta_{H}\Delta_{H}+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right),
\end{align}

\end_inset

which matches the expression found in appendix B of the author's paper 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "brown_symmetry_2015"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equations of motion following from this action are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =-Z_{\Delta}^{-1}\left(m^{2}+\delta m_{0}^{2}\right)v-\frac{\lambda+\delta\lambda_{0}}{3!}v^{3}-\left(N-1\right)\frac{\hbar}{2}\left(Z_{\Delta}\frac{\lambda+\delta\lambda_{1}^{A}}{3}v\right)i\Delta_{G}\left(x,x\right)\nonumber \\
